 or am i thikning about this wrong?\"},\"uuid\":\"bc09495a-aa4e-4898-a9ef-d1eafc3f8408\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-23T20:29:24.082Z\",\"thinkingMetadata\":{\"maxThinkingTokens\":31999},\"permissionMode\":\"acceptEdits\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"bc09495a-aa4e-4898-a9ef-d1eafc3f8408\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"960fa682-812c-41ee-859c-1136484fe07f\",\"version\":\"2.1.42\",\"gitBranch\":\"optimize_claude_start\",\"slug\":\"ancient-mixing-hearth\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_018oafybv5U86Tm4iKg5h81n\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\n\\nYou're right — 10k untracked files is unrealistic. But the dimension wasn't about *untracked* files. Let me clarify what I was trying to test and why it missed.\\n\\nThe `GitObjects` benchmark created 10k orphaned blobs in `.git/objects/` to bloat the packfile. The idea was to simulate a repo with a long history (thousands of commits over months/years = millions of objects). But as I just explained, go-git doesn't scan objects on `PlainOpen`, so this didn't test anything useful.\\n\\nWhat a real customer repo looks like:\\n- **Tracked files in the tree**: 5k-50k (monorepo), but session-start doesn't walk the tree\\n- **Commits**: 10k-500k over years of history, but session-start doesn't walk history\\n- **Refs**: 100-2000 (feature branches, tags, release branches) — we tested this, it's flat\\n\\nSo none of the \\\"repo size\\\" dimensions matter for session-start because **session-start doesn't touch the worktree, the tree objects, or the commit history**. It only does:\\n1. Subprocess spawns (`git rev-parse` × 7-8)\\n2. Read session state files\\n3. Ref lookups for shadow branches\\n\\nWe've benchmarked 2 and 3 and they're fast. The only thing left that we haven't isolated is **#1 — the `git rev-parse` subprocess spawns**. Those 7-8 spawns account for most of the ~80ms 